fields.description:
This issue was [reported by David Bottger on bitbucket.org|https://bitbucket.org/atlassianlabs/atlassian-bitbucket-diy-backup/issues/1/rsync-fails-during-prepare_backup_home]:
{quote}home-rsync can fail on pre-sync when files are deleted prior to syncing I can create a PR for this, given permission, but basically you just need to allow exit 24 from perform_rsync in prepare_backup_home
{code:java}
function prepare_backup_home {
  check_config_var "BITBUCKET_BACKUP_HOME"
  check_config_var "BITBUCKET_HOME"
  # this run is against live data, it is ok to fail due to vanished source files
  (perform_rsync) || EC=$? && if [ "$EC" != 24 ] && [ "$EC" != "" ]; then exit $EC; fi
}
{code}
{quote}

This bug report describes a possible deadlock that may occur during repository deletion. This is likely specific to the Oracle RDBMS which has more specific risks around locks and unindexed foreign keys[1]

The thread stacks on the system that exhibited this problem showed many threads trying to acquire a DB connection, while 77 of the 80 DB connections were blocked executing statements. The threads holding connections were:

{noformat}
75 in HibernateWatcherDao.findByWatchableAndUser(HibernateWatcherDao.java:69)
{noformat}

The above were probably victims and not involved in the deadlock. But they explain why all DB connections are exhausted.

Then the two that are likely involved in the deadlock:

{noformat}
1 in DriftCommentUpdateProcessor.process(DriftCommentUpdateProcessor.java:190)
{noformat}

{noformat}
1 in HibernatePullRequestDao.deleteByToRepository(HibernatePullRequestDao.java:174)
{noformat}

\[1] https://docs.oracle.com/cd/E11882_01/server.112/e40540/consist.htm#CNCPT1339

h3. Problem Definition
Whilst most of the JMX variables in *set-jmx-opts.(sh|bat)* simply take values, a couple of them also require the Java arguments to be set:

{code}
JMX_REMOTE_RMI_PORT=-Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.rmi.port=3333
RMI_SERVER_HOSTNAME=-Djava.rmi.server.hostname=my.bitbucket.hostname
{code}

h3. Suggested Solution
Allow setting these variables without the Java arg, e.g.

{code}
JMX_REMOTE_RMI_PORT=3333
RMI_SERVER_HOSTNAME=my.bitbucket.hostname
{code}

For backwards compatibility with users already specifying the full Java arg in their environment, *set-jmx-opts.(sh|bat)* may need to support values with *and* without the Java arg present

We would like to be able to scan PRs for changes to specific files and then add people as reviewers based on the changes found.

For example, if PR touches:
{code:java}
**/build.xml
**/build.gradle{code}

 Then add User A, B, C as reviewers (requiring 1 approval)

If PR touches:
{code:java}
**/*.java{code}
then add User D, E and A as reviewers (requiring 2 approvals)

For all else add:

User A, D, E as reviewers requiring 1 approval...

Users should be able to set up their own monitors as well...for example if anyone changes *.sql then add me as a reviewer (but don't require an approval - or else I could block everyone)
